The auto-chosen model is ARIMA(2,0,3) with non-zero mean with the AICc 4455.88. However, after manipulating the parameters, especially changing the d value, I found that ARIMA(3,1,2) will provide a lower AICc, 4441.69. But when sticking with d=0, the arima(2,0,3) model is the best so far.

J01_18_dayofweek <- predict_J01_dayofweek$mean[18]

J01_8_hourofday <- predict_J01_hourofday$mean[8]
J01_9_hourofday <- predict_J01_hourofday$mean[9]
J01_17_hourofday <- predict_J01_hourofday$mean[17]
J01_18_hourofday <- predict_J01_hourofday$mean[18]

J01_8_real <- test[8]
J01_9_real <- test[9]
J01_17_real <- test[17]
J01_18_real <- test[18]

dayofweek_result <- c(J01_8_dayofweek,J01_9_dayofweek,J01_17_dayofweek,J01_18_dayofweek)
hourofday_result <- c(J01_8_hourofday,J01_9_hourofday,J01_17_hourofday,J01_18_hourofday)
real_result <- c(J01_8_real,J01_9_real,J01_17_real,J01_18_real)

df_compare <- data.frame(dayofweek_result, hourofday_result,real_result)

print (df_compare)
##   dayofweek_result hourofday_result real_result
## 1         1205.979         794.1640        1233
## 2         1080.979         854.5382        1110
## 3         1196.979        1139.2999        1142
## 4         1125.979        1041.9611        1129
error_dayofweek <- real_result - dayofweek_result 
error_hourofday <- real_result - hourofday_result

df_error <- data.frame(error_dayofweek, error_hourofday)
print (df_error)
##   error_dayofweek error_hourofday
## 1       27.021445       438.83601
## 2       29.021445       255.46175
## 3      -54.978555         2.70009
## 4        3.021445        87.03887
SSE_dayofweek <- sum(error_dayofweek^2)
SSE_hourofday <- sum(error_hourofday^2)

df_SSE <- data.frame(SSE_dayofweek, SSE_hourofday)
print (df_SSE)
##   SSE_dayofweek SSE_hourofday
## 1      4604.173      265420.8

From the results above, we notice that the SSE for question 4 is much lower than that of question 6. That means we should choose the question 4s model, which is a day of the week seasonal arima model.
